-Assembly | PhD in Biophysics, Emory University, Physics Department - Advisor: Keith Berland, PhD | 2007-2013 || Other |  Collaborated with Emory’s Chemistry Department to uncover nucleation and growth mechanisms of self- || Other | assembling peptide nanotubes using nonlinear optical fluorescence fluctuation spectroscopy and time- || Other | correlated single-photon counting (TCSPC) techniques for fluorescence lifetime imaging microscopy (FLIM). || Other |  Developed a novel fluorescence lifetime and fluorescence correlation spectroscopy (τFCS) analysis technique || Other | combining orthogonal molecular properties with multi-level global data fitting for enhanced sensitivity without"}]'::jsonb, '[{"title":"information extraction.","company":"Imported from resume CSV","description":"Elephas, Madison, WI (remote) | 2021-2024 || Developed and implemented life science data projects comprising data analytics, anomaly detection and machine/deep | Principal Data Scientist, | 2022-2024 | learning across a range of domains including transcriptomics, secretomics, flow cytometry, histology, while continuously advancing multi-photon and fluorescence lifetime imaging analyses in parallel.  Compared and evaluated proprietary, open source, and custom fluorescence lifetime curve fitting software/libraries, and developed custom hybrid automated curve fit and hardware library compromising optical system anomaly detection and instrument response analyses; Developed complimentary phasor space analyses and analytics; Researched and evaluated Clifford algebra for multi-channel phasor combination analyses; Developed model-based and molecular-level two-state system photon histogram simulations for library validation and neural network training; Researched and applied deep learning techniques to determine decay parameters; Developed spatial and temporal entropy-based analyses for feature development; Developed tumor micro-environment ‘niche’ analyses via spatial statistical distribution analyses and graph neural networks; Provided optical and quality assessment of Thorlabs / Swabbian digital FLIM alpha systems via image, histogrammed, and raw photon count analyses. ||  Led data science team during the initial small scale ‘startup’ phase (company size ~30 people), providing | Director of Artificial Intelligence, | 2021-2022 | company leadership data direction, initial data analyses and data management for researcher support, together with quantitative analytics and visualizations. || Emory University, Integrated Cellular Imaging (ICI), Atlanta, GA | 2008-2021 || Core Director, | 2019-2021 || Technical Director, | 2017-2019 || Assistant Scientist, | 2016-2017 || General Core Facility | Senior Research Imaging Specialist, | 2013-2016 | Directed microscopy-based bioimaging services, advancing experimental capabilities, fostering researcher education, and securing funding to maintain cutting-edge technologies and workflows.  Researcher training and education (undergrad, graduate, PI, clinicians) on all/any microscopy technology and quantitative data analyses required to achieve project goals.  Coordination with microscope, camera, and laser companies during debugging issues and for new product evaluation (quantitative hardware level calibrations, test data acquisitions, and ad hoc analyses).  Quantitative microscopy consultations with researchers – from molecular-level labeling to experimental design, data analyses, and visualizations.  Oversaw and coordinated ICI staff activities and direction; supported ICI team performance and training. Researched future technological direction to identify needed capabilities.  Coordinated and developed AWS-based auto-indexing, storage, and archive for researcher data.  Expanded awareness/educational marketing and media; Developed dashboards for internal leadership reporting.  Authored two consecutive successful technical NIH equipment grants (total ~$1.4M) in collaboration with ~20 PIs. Neil R Anthony, PhD neil.anthony@bath.edu Page 2 Quantitative Imaging Demonstrated expertise in advanced microscopy technologies, optical systems, hardware control electronics, optical detectors, and multidimensional image formation, analysis, and visualization.  Pioneered the adoption of emerging deep learning techniques in bio-imaging analyses, investigated and implemented cutting-edge AI models including Noise2Void, Cellpose, StarDist and custom CNN/Unet models for image classification, segmentation, and tracking across a diverse range of biological imaging modalities.  Developed and provided researcher training of proprietary and custom multi-dimensional imaging based analysis software, including segmentation and co-localization, in addition to post analysis analytics and statistics.  Assessment of super resolution techniques, and comparisons within STED manufactures as part of demoing and subsequent grant winning application.  Ported time symmetric APD correlation analysis code to Matlab for application/development scanning STED-FCS technique using Abberior hardware.  Adapted and built open source selective plane illumination light sheet system for ~ 1mm sized samples (spheroids, organoids, drosophila etc); Applied 3D multiview registration algorithms, and 4D visualizations.  Supported and developed lattice light sheet alpha unit from 3i; Understanding and alignment of Fourier optics, and Bessel beam lattice light sheet formation and calibration; created custom HDF5 tiered format and automated space transformations with GPU deconvolutions.  Supported calibration and debug of GE DeltaVision 3D SIM microscope; Understanding and application of structured illumination and Fourier space reconstruction super resolution  Researched and assessed applications of advanced esoteric bio-imaging techniques including holotomography, Raman and Coherent anti-Stokes Raman scattering spectroscopy (CARS).  Proficiency with proprietary and custom multi-dimensional imaging based analysis software (including development of custom code and extensions)"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, 'F:\Resume All 1\Resume PDF\NeilAnthony_PhotonDataScientist_Resume (1).pdf', 'Name: Photon Counting Spatiotemporal Data Scientist

